## ❌ WRONG: Custom Form Field Markup

### Wrong Example 1: Manual HTML Structure

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG: Creating custom form field markup
<div className="w-full md:w-1/2 register-form-mobile-row">
  <div className="register-form-mobile-wrapper md:flex md:items-stretch">
    <label className="w-full md:w-1/4 flex items-center m-0 register-form-label bg-gray-100">
      <span className="text-red-600 mr-1">*</span> User ID
    </label>
    <div className="register-form-mobile-field w-full md:w-3/4 flex items-center">
      <div className="w-full">
        <input
          type="text"
          name="userId"
          className={`w-full border rounded-none px-3 py-2 ${
            errors.userId ? "border-red-500" : ""
          }`}
          value={formData.userId}
          onChange={handleInputChange}
        />
        {errors.userId && (
          <div className="text-red-600 text-sm mt-1 px-2">
            {errors.userId}
          </div>
        )}
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
```

**Why this is WRONG:**

1. ❌ Duplicates code that already exists in `FormField` and `FormInput`
2. ❌ Inconsistent with other forms using components
3. ❌ Harder to maintain - changes require updating multiple files
4. ❌ More prone to errors (border logic, spacing, etc.)
5. ❌ Violates DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle

**Fix:**

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT: Use shared components
<FormField
  label="User ID"
  required
  error={errors.userId}
>
  <FormInput
    type="text"
    name="userId"
    value={formData.userId}
    onChange={handleInputChange}
    error={errors.userId}
  />
</FormField>
```

### Wrong Example 2: Mixing Components and Custom Markup

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG: Mixing component with custom markup
<FormField label="User ID" required>
  <input
    type="text"
    name="userId"
    className="w-full border rounded-none px-3 py-2"
    value={formData.userId}
    onChange={handleInputChange}
  />
  {/* ❌ Manual error handling instead of FormInput */}
  {errors.userId && (
    <div className="text-red-600 text-sm mt-1 px-2">
      {errors.userId}
    </div>
  )}
</FormField>
```

**Why this is WRONG:**

1. ❌ Inconsistent error handling (not using `FormInput`'s built-in error display)
2. ❌ Missing error border styling logic
3. ❌ Duplicates error message markup

**Fix:**

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT: Use FormInput for complete functionality
<FormField label="User ID" required error={errors.userId}>
  <FormInput
    type="text"
    name="userId"
    value={formData.userId}
    onChange={handleInputChange}
    error={errors.userId}
  />
</FormField>
```

### Wrong Example 3: Not Converting Data to Component Format

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG: Passing raw data instead of SelectOption format
<FormField label="Site">
  <FormSelect
    name="siteId"
    value={formData.siteId}
    onChange={handleInputChange}
    options={siteList} // ❌ Wrong format
  />
</FormField>
```

**Why this is WRONG:**

1. ❌ `FormSelect` expects `SelectOption[]` format: `{ value: string, label: string }[]`
2. ❌ TypeScript will show type errors
3. ❌ Component won't render options correctly

**Fix:**

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT: Convert data to SelectOption format
const siteOptions: SelectOption[] = siteList.map((site) => ({
  value: site.siteId,
  label: site.siteNm,
}));

<FormField label="Site">
  <FormSelect
    name="siteId"
    value={formData.siteId}
    onChange={handleInputChange}
    options={siteOptions} // ✅ Correct format
  />
</FormField>
```

