## ❌ WRONG: Inconsistent Button Patterns

### Mistake 1: Wrong Button Text ("취소" instead of "닫기")

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG: Using "취소" instead of "닫기"
<button
  type="button"
  onClick={handleCancel}
>
  취소 {/* ❌ Wrong text */}
</button>
```

**Why this is WRONG:**

1. ❌ **Inconsistent with other forms**: BoardRegisterForm, MemberRegisterForm all use "닫기"
2. ❌ **Semantic difference**: "취소" implies canceling input/operation, "닫기" means closing and returning to list
3. ❌ **Creates UI inconsistency**: Breaks visual and text consistency across application
4. ❌ **Professional appearance**: Mixed button text looks unprofessional

**Root Cause Analysis:**

- **Problem**: Not checking existing forms for standard button text
- **Assumption**: "취소" seems logical for canceling form input
- **Reality**: Standard pattern across all admin forms is "닫기"
- **Solution**: Always check MemberRegisterForm and BoardRegisterForm before implementing

**Fix:**

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT: Use "닫기" (standard text)
<button
  type="button"
  onClick={handleCancel}
>
  닫기 {/* ✅ Correct text */}
</button>
```

### Mistake 2: Wrong Button Order (Close before Register)

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG: Close button before Register button
<div className="flex justify-end gap-2">
  <button
    type="button"
    onClick={handleCancel}
  >
    닫기 {/* ❌ Wrong position - should be right */}
  </button>
  <button
    type="submit"
  >
    등록 {/* ❌ Wrong position - should be left */}
  </button>
</div>
```

**Why this is WRONG:**

1. ❌ **Primary action should be first**: 등록 (primary action) should be on left, 닫기 (secondary action) on right
2. ❌ **Inconsistent with standard pattern**: All other forms use 등록 (left) → 닫기 (right)
3. ❌ **Violates UI/UX best practices**: Primary actions should come before secondary actions
4. ❌ **User confusion**: Users expect primary action (등록) to be first
5. ❌ **Professional appearance**: Reversed order looks like a mistake

**Root Cause Analysis:**

- **Problem**: Implementing buttons without checking standard pattern
- **Assumption**: Button order doesn't matter or can be reversed
- **Reality**: Standard pattern is well-established (등록 left → 닫기 right)
- **Solution**: Always check existing forms and follow established pattern

**Fix:**

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT: Register button left, Close button right
<div className="flex justify-end gap-2">
  <button
    type="submit"
  >
    등록 {/* ✅ Correct position - left */}
  </button>
  <button
    type="button"
    onClick={handleCancel}
  >
    닫기 {/* ✅ Correct position - right */}
  </button>
</div>
```

### Mistake 3: Wrong Button Container Classes

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG: Missing standard classes or wrong structure
<div className="flex justify-end gap-2 px-6 py-4 border-t border-gray-200">
  {/* ❌ border-t should not be here for form buttons */}
  <button>...</button>
  <button>...</button>
</div>
```

**Why this is WRONG:**

1. ❌ **Inconsistent spacing**: `border-t` creates visual separation that may not match other forms
2. ❌ **Standard pattern**: Other forms use `flex justify-end mt-3 gap-2 px-6 py-4` without `border-t`
3. ❌ **Visual inconsistency**: Extra border creates different appearance

**Fix:**

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT: Standard container classes
<div className="flex justify-end mt-3 gap-2 px-6 py-4">
  {/* ✅ No border-t, standard spacing */}
  <button>...</button>
  <button>...</button>
</div>
```

